label.value: type II protein secretion system complex

definition.value: A large protein complex, containing 12-15 subunits, that spans the cell envelope of Gram-negative bacteria and mediates the movement of proteins into the extracellular environment. The complex includes a component in the cytoplasm, an inner membrane subcomplex that reaches into the periplasmic compartment and a secretion pore in the outer membrane. Proteins using the Type II pathway are transported across the cytoplasmic membrane by the Sec or Tat complex.
The part of the cytoskeleton (the internal framework of a cell) composed of actin and associated proteins. Includes actin cytoskeleton-associated complexes.
The part of the cytoskeleton (the internal framework of a cell) composed of microtubules and associated proteins.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with monomeric or multimeric forms of tubulin, including microtubules.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O + Zn2+(out) -eq- ADP + phosphate + Zn2+(in).

Catalysis of the transfer of lipopolysaccharide from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane. A lipopolysaccharide is any of a group of related, structurally complex components of the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria. Lipopolysaccharides consist three covalently linked regions, lipid A, core oligosaccharide, and an O side chain. Lipid A is responsible for the toxicity of the lipopolysaccharide.
Enables the directed movement of short-chain fatty acids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. Short-chain fatty acids are fatty acids with a chain length of less than C6.

label.value: short-chain fatty acid uptake transporter activity

definition.value: Enables the directed movement of short-chain fatty acids into a cell or organelle. Short-chain fatty acids are fatty acids with a chain length of less than C6.
Catalysis of the transfer of a microcin from the outside of a cell to the inside of the cell across a membrane.

label.value: ferrous iron uptake transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Fe2+(out) + energy -eq- Fe2+(in).

Enables the directed movement of peptidoglycan peptides into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. Peptidoglycan peptides are the oligopeptides found in peptidoglycan networks which cross-link the polysaccharide chains.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a toxic substance, a poisonous substance that causes damage to biological systems.

label.value: quaternary ammonium group transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of quaternary ammonium groups from one side of a membrane to the other. Quaternary ammonium groups are any compound that can be regarded as derived from ammonium hydroxide or an ammonium salt by replacement of all four hydrogen atoms of the NH4+ ion by organic groups.

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  quaternary ammonium group(out) + H+(out) -eq- quaternary ammonium group(in) + H+(in).

Catalysis of the transfer of tellurite from the outside of a cell to the inside across a membrane -  tellurite(out) + H+(out) -eq- tellurite(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  alanine(out) + Na+(out) -eq- alanine(in) + Na+(in).

label.value: branched-chain amino acid - sodium symporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  branched-chain amino acid(out) + cation(out) -eq- branched-chain amino acid(in) + cation(in).

label.value: branched-chain amino acid transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of branched-chain amino acids from one side of a membrane to the other. Branched-chain amino acids are amino acids with a branched carbon skeleton without rings.

Catalysis of the transfer of formate from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.
Catalysis of the transfer of L-lysine from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.

label.value: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of ions, phosphorylative mechanism

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the transport of ions across a membrane. The reaction is characterized by the transient formation of a high-energy aspartyl-phosphoryl-enzyme intermediate.

Enables the directed movement of nicotinamide mononucleotide into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. Nicotinamide mononucleotide is a ribonucleotide in which the nitrogenous base, nicotinamide, is in beta-n-glycosidic linkage with the c-1 position of d-ribose. It is a constituent of NAD and NADP.
Catalysis of the transfer of an alcohol from one side of the membrane to the other. An alcohol is any carbon compound that contains a hydroxyl group.
